The steps to configure Nginx as a reverse proxy for a Node.js application are as follows:

1. Install Nginx:
 - On Ubuntu, run the commands `sudo apt update` and `sudo apt install nginx`.

2. Create a configuration file for the application:
 - Create a new file in the `/etc/nginx/sites-available/` directory with your application name.
 - Add the following configuration:
 ```nginx
 server {
 listen 80;
 server_name your_domain.com;

 location / {
 proxy_pass http://localhost:3000;
 proxy_http_version 1.1;
 proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;
 proxy_set_header Connection 'upgrade';
 proxy_set_header Host $host;
 proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;
 }
 }
 ```

3. Enable configuration:
- Create a link to the `sites-enabled` directory: `sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/your_app /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/`.

4. Test Nginx configuration:
- Run the command `sudo nginx -t` to check for errors.

5. Restart Nginx:
- Run the command `sudo systemctl restart nginx`.

Once you complete the above steps, Nginx will forward requests to your Node.js application.

