Steps to implement error handling in an Express.js application:

1. Use a middleware to handle errors:
```javascript
function errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(500).send('Something went wrong!');
}
```

2. Define a route that could throw an error:
```javascript
app.get('/api/error', (req, res) => {
  throw new Error('An error occurred');
});
```

3. Attach the error handling middleware to the app after defining all your routes:
```javascript
app.use(errorHandler);
```

4. Customize the error handling logic to handle different error types, such as 404 for not found errors or 400 for bad requests.
```javascript
function errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {
  if (err.message === 'Not Found') {
    return res.status(404).send('Resource not found');
  }
  res.status(500).send('Server error');
}
```

5. Ensure all unhandled errors are caught and properly logged for debugging purposes.

 Reference: https://expressjs.com/en/guide/using-middleware.html#error-handling

