Steps to optimize the performance of a React application:

1. Use React's `React.memo` for functional components to prevent unnecessary re-renders:
```javascript
const MyComponent = React.memo(({ data }) => {
  return <div>{data}</div>;
});
```

2. Use `shouldComponentUpdate` for class components to control when re-rendering happens:
```javascript
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
  shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps) {
    return nextProps.data !== this.props.data;
  }
}
```

3. Code-split your application using React's `React.lazy` and `Suspense` to load only the necessary parts of your app:
```javascript
const OtherComponent = React.lazy(() => import('./OtherComponent'));

<Suspense fallback={<div>Loading...</div>}>
  <OtherComponent />
</Suspense>
```

4. Use the `useEffect` hook to perform side effects only when necessary, avoiding unnecessary re-renders:
```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData();
}, []); // Runs only once, after the initial render
```

5. Optimize images and assets by using formats like WebP and compressing images.

 Reference: https://reactjs.org/docs/optimizing-performance.html

