Difference between `let` and `var`:

1. `let` has block-level scope, while `var` has function-level scope.
2. `let` cannot be redeclared within the same scope, while `var` can.
3. `let` is hoisted but not initialized, whereas `var` is hoisted and initialized to `undefined`.

Example with `let`:
```javascript
let x = 10;
if (true) {
  let x = 20;
  console.log(x);  // Output: 20
}
console.log(x);  // Output: 10
```

Example with `var`:
```javascript
var x = 10;
if (true) {
  var x = 20;
  console.log(x);  // Output: 20
}
console.log(x);  // Output: 20
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/let

