1. Define an asynchronous function using the `async` keyword:
```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  return 'Data fetched';
}
```
2. Use the `await` keyword to pause execution until a promise resolves:
```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com');
  return data.json();
}
```
3. Handle errors using `try/catch`:
```javascript
try {
  const result = await fetchData();
  console.log(result);
} catch (err) {
  console.error('Error:', err);
}
```
4. Async/await simplifies promise chaining and improves code readability.

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/async_function

