Steps to handle errors in Node.js:

1. Use try-catch blocks for synchronous code:
```javascript
try {
  throw new Error('Something went wrong');
} catch (err) {
  console.error(err.message);
}
```
2. For asynchronous code, use `.catch()` to handle promises:
```javascript
someAsyncFunction()
  .then((result) => console.log(result))
  .catch((err) => console.error(err.message));
```
3. You can also use the `process.on('uncaughtException')` event to handle uncaught exceptions:
```javascript
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => {
  console.error('Uncaught exception: ', err.message);
  process.exit(1);  // Exit the process
});
```
4. Proper error handling ensures that your Node.js app is more stable and user-friendly.

 Reference: https://nodejs.org/en/docs/guides/error-handling/

