A higher-order function is a function that can accept a function as an argument, return a function as a result, or both.

Example of passing a function as an argument:
```javascript
function greet(name) {
  return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}
function processGreeting(fn, name) {
  console.log(fn(name));
}
processGreeting(greet, 'John'); // Output: Hello, John!
```

Example of returning a function:
```javascript
function multiplyBy(x) {
  return function(y) {
    return x * y;
  };
}
const multiplyByTwo = multiplyBy(2);
console.log(multiplyByTwo(5)); // Output: 10
```

 Reference: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Functions

